# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alcohol-in-malaysia
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/2018-malaysia-methanol-poisonings] The **2018 Malaysia methanol poisonings** occurred in September 2018 in three states and two federal territories in Malaysia comprising Selangor (64 cases), Kuala Lumpur and Putrajaya (18 cases), Perak (13 cases) and Negeri Sembilan (3 cases).
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/2018-malaysia-methanol-poisonings] Until October, 45 people from the total of 98 cases have been reported dead by the Malaysian Health Ministry.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/2018-malaysia-methanol-poisonings] Most of the victims were foreign workers from Bangladesh, Indonesia, Myanmar, and Nepal, as well as several Malaysians.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/2018-malaysia-methanol-poisonings] An investigation found that most of the victims had bought a cheap liquor from *hole in the wall* stores in bid to evade the tax rates on Malaysian alcohols that range from 150–560%.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/2018-malaysia-methanol-poisonings] The Malaysian government responded to the incident by confiscating 15,630 bottles of liquor from 1,961 premises across the country.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/2018-malaysia-methanol-poisonings] Around 30 people in connection with the distribution have been arrested despite little response and insufficient enforcement of the black market in the country from the authorities has attracted criticism.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/acar] Through examining the etymology, the similar sounding name strongly suggests that indeed acar was derived from the Indian achar pickle.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/acar] Indian achar was transmitted in antiquity to the maritime realm of Southeast Asia, which today is recognized as acar in Indonesia, Malaysia, Singapore and Brunei, and then on to the Philippines as *atchara*.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/acar] The adoption of this vegetable pickling technique possibly took place during the Srivijaya period between 7th to 13th century.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/acar] British navigator Thomas Forrest wrote that acar made of salted limes and palm vinegar was often of use to Coromandel Muslim sailors (*Chulias*) to prevent scurvy and was sold as far as Aceh.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/acar] The Southeast Asian variations are usually made from different vegetables such as cucumber, carrots, cabbage, shallot, bird's eye chili and yardlong beans, which are pickled in vinegar, sometimes with kaffir lime to add citrus aroma, and also dried chillies.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/acar] Some recipes might have the vegetables tossed in ground peanuts.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/acar] *Acar* is commonly served as a condiment to be eaten with a main course, such as *martabak*, *nasi goreng* (fried rice), satay, and almost all varieties of *soto*.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/acar] Just like common pickles, the sour taste of *acar* is meant to freshen up a meal, especially fishy dishes such as *ikan bakar* (grilled fish) or rich and oily dishes such as mutton satay to neutralize the fat.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/acar] In Indonesia, acar is commonly made from small chunks of cucumber, carrot, shallot, bird's eye chili and occasionally pineapple, and marinated in a sweet and sour solution of sugar and vinegar.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/acar] Some households add lemongrass or ginger to spice it up.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/acar] It is usually used as condiment to accompany grilled foods such as satay.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/acar] Nevertheless, *acar* can also be consumed as a whole, complete dish.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/acar] For example, *ikan acar kuning* is a fish dish (gourami, mackerel or tilapia) served in *acar* pickles of cucumber, carrot, shallot and red chili, mixed with yellow spice paste made of ground turmeric, candlenut, ginger, garlic and shallot.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/acar] It is known as *atjar* (pickle) in Dutch cuisine, derived from Indonesian *acar*, since the Netherlands and Indonesia share colonial ties.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/acar] Variations of Malaysian and Singaporean *acar* include *acar awak* or Nyonya *acar* and Malay *acar*.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/acar] *Acar awak* is more elaborate, containing additional vegetables such as eggplants as well as aromatic spices in the pickling mix.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/acar] The salad has also been adopted into Thai cuisine, where it is called *achat* (Thai: อาจาด, pronounced [ʔāː.t͡ɕàːt]).
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/acar] It is made with cucumber, red chilies, red onions or shallots, vinegar, sugar and salt.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/acar] It is served as a side dish with the Thai version of satay (Thai: สะเต๊ะ).
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/acar] With Indian and Malay slaves initially brought by the British Empire, *atchar* became a favourite condiment in South Africa.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/acar] The local variation is usually made with green mangoes.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/adhirasam] Adhirasam is a popular as an offering to the relatives during Deepavali and Ganesha Chaturthi festivals, both at home and in temples in Tamil Nadu and Karnataka.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/adhirasam] The earliest documented references to Adhirasam emerge from medieval Tamil kingdoms, particularly the Chola dynasty, where it appeared as a favored item in royal feasts and temple rituals.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/adhirasam] According to inscriptions from the 16th century, during the reign of Vijayanagara emperor Krishnadevaraya, the sweet was made from rice flour, jaggery, ghee and pepper.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/adhirasam] At the annual festival at the Panchavarnesvar Temple in Thirunallur (located near Kumbakonam, Tamil Nadu), an offering of 6000 Adhirasams along with 6000 vadas is made to the Gods; the entire lot is cooked in the temple kitchen between sunrise and 11 pm, for the prayers that take place at midnight.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/adhirasam] It is a popular Deepavali sweet preparation for Tamil people.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/adhirasam] The authentic preparation takes about a week.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/adhirasam] First the rice is soaked in water and dried in shade and ground into a fine powder when the rice is 3/4th dried and retains some moisture.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/adhirasam] For adding sweet "vellam" (jaggery in Tamil) is melted in water by boiling it till it reaches soft-ball consistency (235–240 °F (113–116 °C), if using a candy thermometer) and added to the rice flour along with some powdered cardamom to make a thick dough.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/adhirasam] It is then transferred to an earthenware pot and the top of the pot is closed with a thin white cloth.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/adhirasam] It is then allowed to ferment for about 3–5 days by placing it in the sunlight during the day.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/adhirasam] Finally, when the batter is ready for preparation, small balls of the dough is taken and flattened using fingers in a small piece of oil-brushed banana leaf and deep fried in oil until golden brown.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/adhirasam] Then it is pressed with a flat bottomed bowl to remove the excess oil.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/ais-kacang] Traditionally, an ice shaving machine is used to churn out the shaved ice used in the dessert, originally hand cranked but now more often motorised.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/ais-kacang] Many Southeast Asian coffee shops, hawker centres and food courts sell this dessert.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/ais-kacang] Early versions of ais kacang was first known to have been prepared around the time before and after the First World War, where the costs of ice manufacturing was becoming more affordable.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/ais-kacang] An earlier variant of the Singaporean dish was described as green, made from shaved ice, paired with syrups, *soaked seeds* and seaweed jelly and was sold mainly by street vendors.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/ais-kacang] The dish underwent many different alterations and variants throughout the history of Singapore, where during the 1920s, one version of it was described as shaved ice topped with rose water, lime or liquorice.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/ais-kacang] A version of the dish, known as Kachang mera, was also sold during the 1930s.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/ais-kacang] By the 1940s, the version of the dish described as having "shaved ice heaped into a little mountain", topped with red beans, "a Chinese grape-like fruit", syrup, and condensed or evaporated milk, similar to how it is being prepared today, began to appear.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/ais-kacang] Some earlier variants of ais kacang are no longer sold, such as the ice ball version of the dessert, which was popular during the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/ais-kacang] In Malaysia, variants now contain a large serving of *attap chee* (palm seed), red beans, sweet corn, grass jelly, roasted peanuts, and cubes of agar agar as common ingredients.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/ais-kacang] Other less common ingredients include aloe vera, *cendol*, *nata de coco*, and ice cream.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/ais-kacang] A final topping of evaporated milk, condensed milk, or coconut milk is drizzled over the mountain of ice along with red rose syrup and sarsi syrup.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/ais-kacang] Some stalls have even introduced novelty toppings such as durian and chocolate syrup.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/ais-kacang] There are also versions that shun the multi-coloured syrup and are served instead with just a drizzling of palm sugar syrup.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/ais-kacang] In Singapore, traditional ice kachang is usually made from shaved ice, packed into a mountain-like shape and consists of red beans, creamed corn, attap chee, cendol, and grass jelly, similar to the Malaysian version, and drizzled with syrups made from gula melaka, red rose syrup, and pandan syrup.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/ais-kacang] The dish has evolved to include fruits such as durian, mango, toppings such as Milo, peanuts, and sago pearls among others.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol has a variety of adverse effects.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Short-term adverse effects include generalized impairment of neurocognitive function, dizziness, nausea, vomiting, and symptoms of hangover.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol is addictive and can result in alcohol use disorder, dependence, and withdrawal upon cessation.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] The adverse effects of alcohol on health are most significant when it is used in excessive quantities or with heavy frequency.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] However, in 2023, the World Health Organization published a statement in The Lancet Public Health that concluded, "no safe amount of alcohol consumption for cancers and health can be established".
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] In high amounts, alcohol may cause loss of consciousness or, in severe cases, death.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Many governmental agencies and organizations issue alcohol consumption recommendations.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol has been produced and consumed by humans for its psychoactive effects since at least 13,000 years ago, when the earliest known beer was brewed by the Natufian culture in the Middle East.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol is the second most consumed psychoactive drug globally, behind caffeine, with global sales of alcoholic beverages exceeding US$1.5 trillion in 2017.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Drinking alcohol is generally socially acceptable and is legal in most countries, unlike with many other recreational substances.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] However, there are often restrictions on alcohol sale and use, for instance a minimum age for drinking and laws against public drinking and drinking and driving.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol has considerable societal and cultural significance and has important social roles in much of the world.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Drinking establishments, such as bars and nightclubs, revolve primarily around the sale and consumption of alcoholic beverages, and parties, festivals, and social gatherings commonly involve alcohol consumption.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol is related to various societal problems, including drunk driving, accidental injuries, sexual assaults, domestic abuse, and violent crime.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol remains illegal for sale and consumption in a number of countries, mainly in the Middle East.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] While some religions, including Islam, prohibit alcohol consumption, other religions, such as Christianity and Shinto, utilize alcohol in sacrament and libation.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Ethanol is commonly consumed as the recreational active substance of alcoholic beverages such as beer, wine, and spirits.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Consumption in social settings may enhance sociability.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] While research on the societal benefits of alcohol is rare, in a study from the UK, regular but moderate drinking was correlated with happiness, feeling that life was worthwhile, and satisfaction with life.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Community pubs had less variation in visible group sizes and longer, more focused conversations than those in city centre bars.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Drinking regularly at a community pub led to higher trust in others and better networking with the local community, compared to non-drinkers and city centre bar drinkers.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] However, according to a causal path analysis, alcohol consumption was not the cause, but rather satisfaction with life resulted in greater happiness and an inclination to visit pubs and develop a regular drinking venue.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] The US Department of Agriculture (USDA) uses a figure of 6.93 kilocalories (29.0 kJ) per gram of alcohol (5.47 kcal or 22.9 kJ per mL) for calculating food energy.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] For distilled spirits, a standard serving in the United States is 44 mL (1.5 US fl oz), which at 40% ethanol (80 proof), would be 14 grams and 98 calories.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Alcoholic drinks are considered empty calorie foods because other than food energy they contribute no essential nutrients.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] However, alcohol is a significant source of food energy for individuals with alcoholism and those who engage in binge drinking.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] For example, individuals with drunkorexia engage in the combination of self-imposed malnutrition and binge drinking.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] In alcoholics who get most of their daily calories from alcohol, a deficiency of thiamine (vitamin B1) can produce Korsakoff syndrome, which is associated with serious brain damage.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] When fomepizole is not available, ethanol can be used to treat or prevent methanol or ethylene glycol poisoning.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] The rate-limiting steps for the elimination of ethanol are in common with these substances, so it competes with other alcohols for the alcohol dehydrogenase enzyme.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Methanol itself is not highly toxic, but its metabolites formaldehyde and formic acid are; therefore, to reduce the rate of production and concentration of these harmful metabolites, ethanol can be ingested or injected.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] This avoids the production of toxic aldehyde and carboxylic acid derivatives, and reduces the more serious toxic effects of the glycols when crystallized in the kidneys.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Ethylene glycol poisoning can be treated in the same way.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol has a long association of military use, and has been called "liquid courage" for its role in preparing troops for battle, anesthetize injured soldiers, and celebrate military victories.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] It has also served as a coping mechanism for combat stress reactions and a means of decompression from combat to everyday life.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol can have analgesic (pain-relieving) effects, which is why some people with chronic pain turn to alcohol to self-medicate and try to alleviate their physical discomfort.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] People with social anxiety disorder commonly self-medicate with alcohol to overcome their highly set inhibitions.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] However, self-medicating excessively for prolonged periods of time with alcohol often makes the symptoms of anxiety or depression worse.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] This is believed to occur as a result of the changes in brain chemistry from long-term use.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] A 2023 systematic review highlights the non-addictive use of alcohol for managing developmental issues, personality traits, and psychiatric symptoms, emphasizing the need for informed, harm-controlled approaches to alcohol consumption within a personalized health policy framework.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Ethanol is classified as a teratogen—a substance known to cause birth defects; according to the U.S.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC), alcohol consumption by women who are not using birth control increases the risk of fetal alcohol spectrum disorders (FASDs).
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] This group of conditions encompasses fetal alcohol syndrome, partial fetal alcohol syndrome, alcohol-related neurodevelopmental disorder, static encephalopathy, and alcohol-related birth defects.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] The CDC currently recommends complete abstinence from alcoholic beverages for women of child-bearing age who are pregnant or trying to become pregnant.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] In patients who have a peptic ulcer disease (PUD), the mucosal layer is broken down by ethanol.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] PUD is commonly associated with the bacteria *Helicobacter pylori*, which secretes a toxin that weakens the mucosal wall, allowing acid and protein enzymes to penetrate the weakened barrier.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Because alcohol stimulates the stomach to secrete acid, a person with PUD should avoid drinking alcohol on an empty stomach.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Drinking alcohol causes more acid release, which further damages the already-weakened stomach wall.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Complications of this disease could include a burning pain in the abdomen, bloating, and, in severe cases, the presence of dark black stools indicate internal bleeding.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] A person who drinks alcohol regularly is strongly advised to reduce their intake to prevent PUD aggravation.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Ethanol-containing beverages can cause alcohol flush reactions, exacerbations of rhinitis, and, more seriously and commonly, bronchoconstriction in patients with a history of asthma, and in some cases, urticarial skin eruptions, and systemic dermatitis.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol consumption can cause hypoglycemia in diabetics on certain medications, such as insulin or sulfonylurea, by blocking gluconeogenesis.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol increases insulin response to glucose promoting fat storage and hindering carbohydrate and fat oxidation.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] This excess processing in the liver acetyl CoA can lead to fatty liver disease and eventually alcoholic liver disease.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] This progression can lead to further complications, alcohol-related liver disease may cause exocrine pancreatic insufficiency, the inability to properly digest food due to a lack or reduction of digestive enzymes made by the pancreas.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol has a variety of short-term and long-term adverse effects.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol has both short-term, and long-term effects on the memory, and sleep.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] It also has reinforcement-related adverse effects, including alcoholism, dependence, and withdrawal.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol use is directly related to considerable morbidity and mortality, for instance due to intoxication and alcohol-related health problems.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] The World Health Organization advises that there is no safe level of alcohol consumption.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Many of the toxic and unpleasant actions of alcohol in the body are mediated by its carcinogenic byproduct acetaldehyde.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] The amount of ethanol in the body is typically quantified by blood alcohol content (BAC); weight of ethanol per unit volume of blood.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Small doses of ethanol, in general, are stimulant-like and produce euphoria and relaxation; people experiencing these symptoms tend to become talkative and less inhibited, and may exhibit poor judgement.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] At higher dosages (BAC > 1 gram/liter), ethanol acts as a central nervous system (CNS) depressant, producing at progressively higher dosages, impaired sensory and motor function, slowed cognition, stupefaction, unconsciousness, and possible death.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] A hangover is the experience of various unpleasant physiological and psychological effects usually following the consumption of alcohol, such as wine, beer, and liquor.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Hangovers can last for several hours or for more than 24 hours.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] The long-term effects of alcohol have been extensively researched.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] The health effects of long-term alcohol consumption vary depending on the amount consumed.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Even light drinking poses health risks, but atypically small amounts of alcohol may have health benefits.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Alcoholism causes severe health consequences which outweigh any potential benefits.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Long-term alcohol consumption is capable of damaging nearly every organ and system in the body.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] In addition, damage to the central nervous system and peripheral nervous system (e.g., painful peripheral neuropathy) can occur from chronic heavy alcohol consumption.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] There is also an increased risk for accidental injuries, for example, those sustained in traffic accidents and falls.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Excessive alcohol consumption can have a negative impact on aging.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Conversely, light intake of alcohol may have some beneficial effects.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] The association of alcohol intake with reduced cardiovascular risk has been noted since 1904 and remains even after adjusting for known confounders.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Light alcohol intake is also associated with reduced risk of type 2 diabetes, gastritis, and cholelithiasis.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] However, these are only observational studies and high-quality evidence for the beneficial effects of alcohol is nonexistent.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol causes a plethora of detrimental effects in society.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Addiction experts in psychiatry, chemistry, pharmacology, forensic science, epidemiology, and the police and legal services engaged in delphic analysis regarding 20 popular recreational substances.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol was ranked 6th in dependence, 11th in physical harm, and 2nd in social harm.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol use is stereotypically associated with crime, more so than other drugs like marijuana.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Many emergency room visits involve alcohol use.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] As many as 15% of employees show problematic alcohol-related behaviors in the workplace, such as drinking before going to work or even drinking on the job.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Drunk dialing refers to an intoxicated person making phone calls that they would not likely make if sober.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol availability and consumption rates and alcohol rates are positively associated with nuisance, loitering, panhandling, and disorderly conduct in open spaces.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Binge drinking, or heavy episodic drinking, is drinking alcoholic beverages with an intention of becoming intoxicated by heavy consumption of alcohol over a short period of time.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Binge drinking is associated with risks such as suicide, sexual assault, cardiovascular issues, and brain damage, more acutely than alcohol use in general.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Alcoholism or its medical diagnosis *alcohol use disorder* refers to alcohol addiction, alcohol dependence, dipsomania, and/or alcohol abuse.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] It is a major problem and many health problems as well as death can result from excessive alcohol use.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol dependence is linked to a lifespan that is reduced by about 12 years relative to the average person.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] In 2004, it was estimated that 4% of deaths worldwide were attributable to alcohol use.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Deaths from alcohol are split about evenly between acute causes (e.g., overdose, accidents) and chronic conditions.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] The leading chronic alcohol-related condition associated with death is alcoholic liver disease.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol dependence is also associated with cognitive impairment and organic brain damage.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Some researchers have found that even one alcoholic drink a day increases an individual's risk of health problems by 0.4%.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Two or more consecutive alcohol-free days a week have been recommended to improve health and break dependence.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Discontinuation of alcohol after extended heavy use and associated tolerance development (resulting in dependence) can result in alcohol withdrawal.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol is one of the most dangerous drugs to withdraw from.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol withdrawal can cause confusion, paranoia, anxiety, insomnia, agitation, tremors, fever, nausea, vomiting, autonomic dysfunction, seizures, and hallucinations.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Delirium tremens is a condition that develops in some cases of severe withdrawal, with onset typically 48–72 hours after discontinuation.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] It is considered a medical emergency and should be treated in an inpatient or intensive care unit.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Symptoms of ethanol overdose may include nausea, vomiting, CNS depression, coma, acute respiratory failure, or death.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Levels of even less than 0.1% can cause intoxication, with unconsciousness often occurring at 0.3–0.4%.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Death from ethanol consumption is possible when blood alcohol levels reach 0.4%.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] A blood level of 0.5% or more is commonly fatal.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] The oral median lethal dose (LD50) of ethanol in rats is 5,628 mg/kg.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Directly translated to human beings, this would mean that if a person who weighs 70 kg (150 lb) drank a 500 mL (17 US fl oz) glass of pure ethanol, they would have an estimated 50% risk of dying.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] The highest blood alcohol level ever recorded, in which the subject survived, is 1.41%.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol-induced dose dumping (AIDD) is an unintended rapid release of large amounts of a given drug, when administered through a modified-release dosage while co-ingesting ethanol.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] This is considered a pharmaceutical disadvantage due to the high risk of causing drug-induced toxicity by increasing the absorption and serum concentration above the therapeutic window of the drug.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] The best way to prevent this interaction is by avoiding the co-ingestion of both substances or using specific controlled-release formulations that are resistant to AIDD.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Particular drugs of concern are antipsychotics and certain antidepressants.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol can intensify the sedation caused by hypnotics and sedatives such as barbiturates, benzodiazepines, sedative antihistamines, opioids, nonbenzodiazepines/Z-drugs (such as zolpidem and zopiclone).
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Disulfiram inhibits the enzyme acetaldehyde dehydrogenase, which in turn results in buildup of acetaldehyde, a toxic metabolite of ethanol with unpleasant effects.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] The medication or drug is commonly used to treat alcohol use disorder, and results in immediate hangover-like symptoms upon consumption of alcohol, this effect is widely known as disulfiram effect.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Metronidazole is an antibacterial agent that kills bacteria by damaging cellular DNA and hence cellular function.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Metronidazole is usually given to people who have diarrhea caused by *Clostridioides difficile* bacteria.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Patients who are taking metronidazole are sometimes advised to avoid alcohol, even after 1 hour following the last dose.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Although older data suggested a possible disulfiram-like effect of metronidazole, newer data has challenged this and suggests it does not actually have this effect.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) and alcohol both increase gastrointestinal events such as gastrointestinal bleeding and peptic ulcers.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Taking the two together further increases the risk additively.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] The risk of stomach bleeding is still increased when aspirin is taken with alcohol or warfarin.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Ethanol enhances the bioavailability of methylphenidate (elevated plasma dexmethylphenidate).
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Ethylphenidate formation appears to be more common when large quantities of methylphenidate and alcohol are consumed at the same time, such as in non-medical use or overdose scenarios.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] However, only a small percent of the consumed methylphenidate is converted to ethylphenidate.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] While nicotinis mimic the name of classic cocktails like the appletini (their name deriving from "martini"), combining nicotine with alcohol may cause adverse effects.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Tobacco and nicotine actually heighten cravings for alcohol, making this a risky mix.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Controlled animal and human studies showed that caffeine (energy drinks) in combination with alcohol increased the craving for more alcohol more strongly than alcohol alone.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] These findings correspond to epidemiological data that people who consume energy drinks generally showed an increased tendency to take alcohol and other substances.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Ethanol interacts with cocaine *in vivo* to produce cocaethylene, another psychoactive substance which may be substantially more cardiotoxic than either cocaine or alcohol by themselves.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] In combination with cannabis, ethanol increases plasma tetrahydrocannabinol levels, which suggests that ethanol may increase the absorption of tetrahydrocannabinol.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Excessive use of alcohol is known to affect the metabolism of warfarin and can elevate the INR, and thus increase the risk of bleeding.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Food and Drug Administration (FDA) product insert on warfarin states that alcohol should be avoided.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] The Cleveland Clinic suggests that when taking warfarin one should not drink more than "one beer, 6 oz of wine, or one shot of alcohol per day".
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Use of isoniazid should be carefully monitored in daily alcohol drinkers since they may be more likely to develop isoniazid-associated hepatitis.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol works in the brain primarily by increasing the effects of GABA (γ-aminobutyric acid), the major inhibitory neurotransmitter in the brain; by facilitating GABA's actions in the GABAA receptor, alcohol suppresses the activity of the central nervous system.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol also directly affects a number of other neurotransmitter systems including those of glutamate, glycine, acetylcholine, and serotonin.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] The pleasurable effects of alcohol ingestion are the result of increased levels of dopamine and endogenous opioids in the reward pathways of the brain.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] After oral ingestion, ethanol is absorbed via the stomach and intestines into the bloodstream.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Ethanol is highly water-soluble and diffuses passively throughout the entire body, including the brain.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Soon after ingestion, it begins to be metabolized, 90% or more by the liver.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] One standard drink is sufficient to almost completely saturate the liver's capacity to metabolize alcohol.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] The main metabolite is acetaldehyde, a toxic carcinogen.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Acetaldehyde is then further metabolized into ionic acetate by the enzyme aldehyde dehydrogenase (ALDH).
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Acetate is not carcinogenic and has low toxicity, but has been implicated in causing hangovers.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Acetate is further broken down into carbon dioxide and water and eventually eliminated from the body through urine and breath.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] 5 to 10% of ethanol is excreted unchanged in the breath, urine, and sweat.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Ethanol is also known chemically as alcohol, ethyl alcohol, or drinking alcohol.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] It is a simple alcohol with a molecular formula of C2H6O and a molecular weight of 46.0684 g/mol.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] The molecular formula of ethanol may also be written as CH3−CH2−OH or as C2H5−OH.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] The latter can also be thought of as an ethyl group linked to a hydroxyl (alcohol) group and can be abbreviated as EtOH.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Ethanol is a volatile, flammable, colorless liquid with a slight characteristic odor.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Aside from its use as a psychoactive and recreational substance, ethanol is also commonly used as an antiseptic and disinfectant, a chemical and medicinal solvent, and a fuel.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Ethanol is only one of several types of chemical alcohols, and has a variety of analogues.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Most other alcohols are considered poisonous.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] In general, higher alcohols are less toxic.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Alcoholic beverages are sometimes laced with toxic alcohols.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] The toxicity of isopropyl alcohol is about twice that of ethanol; a mild, brief exposure to isopropyl alcohol is unlikely to cause any serious harm, although ingesting significant quantities can lead to vomiting, abdominal pain, and internal bleeding.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Ingestion of as little as 3.16 grams of methanol can cause irreversible optic nerve damage, and the oral LD50 for humans is estimated to be 56.2 grams.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Many methanol poisoning incidents have occurred through history. n-Butanol is reported to produce similar effects to those of ethanol and relatively low toxicity (one-sixth of that of ethanol in one rat study).
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] However, its vapors can produce eye irritation, and inhalation can cause pulmonary edema.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Acetone (propanone) is a ketone rather than an alcohol, and is reported to produce similar toxic effects; it can be extremely damaging to the cornea.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Although ethanol is the most prevalent alcohol in alcoholic beverages, alcoholic beverages contain several types of psychoactive alcohols, that are categorized as primary, secondary, or tertiary.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Primary and secondary alcohols, are oxidized to aldehydes, and ketones, respectively, while tertiary alcohols are generally resistant to oxidation.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] The Lucas test differentiates between primary, secondary, and tertiary alcohols.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] The tertiary alcohol *tert*-amyl alcohol (TAA), also known as 2-methylbutan-2-ol (2M2B), has a history of use as a hypnotic and anesthetic, as do other tertiary alcohols such as methylpentynol, ethchlorvynol, and chloralodol.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Unlike primary alcohols like ethanol, these tertiary alcohols cannot be oxidized into aldehyde or carboxylic acid metabolites, which are often toxic, and for this reason, these compounds are safer in comparison.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Other relatives of ethanol with similar effects include chloral hydrate, paraldehyde, and many volatile and inhalational anesthetics (e.g., chloroform, diethyl ether, and isoflurane).
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Ethanol is produced naturally as a byproduct of the metabolic processes of yeast and hence is present in any yeast habitat, including even endogenously in humans, but it does not cause raised blood alcohol content as seen in the rare medical condition auto-brewery syndrome (ABS).
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] It is manufactured through hydration of ethylene or by brewing via fermentation of sugars with yeast (most commonly *Saccharomyces cerevisiae*).
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] The sugars are commonly obtained from sources like steeped cereal grains (e.g., barley), grape juice, and sugarcane products (e.g., molasses, sugarcane juice).
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Ethanol–water mixture which can be further purified via distillation.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol is one of the oldest recreational drugs.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] The word "Alcohol" originates from the Arabic word *al-kuhul,* which refers to a fine metallic powder that was used to paint the eyelids darker.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Alcoholic beverages have been produced since the Neolithic period, as early as 7000 BC in China.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol was brewed as early as 7,000 to 6,650 BCE in northern China.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] The earliest evidence of winemaking was dated at 6,000 to 5,800 BCE in Georgia in the South Caucasus.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Beer was likely brewed from barley as early as 13,000 years ago in the Middle East.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Pliny the Elder wrote about the *golden age* of winemaking in Rome, the 2nd century BCE (200–100 BCE), when vineyards were planted.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] The Gin Craze was a period in the first half of the 18th century when the consumption of gin increased rapidly in Great Britain, especially in London.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] By 1743, The average English person was drinking 2.2 gallons (10 litres) of gin per year.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] The Sale of Spirits Act 1750 (commonly known as the Gin Act 1751) was an Act of the Parliament of Great Britain (24 Geo.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] 40) which was enacted to reduce the consumption of gin and other distilled spirits, a popular pastime that was regarded as one of the primary causes of crime in London.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] The rum ration (also called the tot) was a daily amount of rum given to sailors on Royal Navy ships.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] It started 1866 and was abolished in 1970 after concerns that the intake of strong alcohol would lead to unsteady hands when working machinery.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] The Andrew Johnson alcoholism debate is the dispute, originally conducted among the general public, and now typically a question for historians, about whether or not Andrew Johnson, the 17th president of the United States (1865–1869), drank to excess.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] The prohibition in the United States era was the period from 1920 to 1933 when the United States prohibited the production, importation, transportation, and sale of alcoholic beverages.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] The nationwide ban on alcoholic beverages, was repealed by the passage of the Twenty-first Amendment to the United States Constitution on December 5, 1933.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] The Bratt System was a system that was used in Sweden (1919–1955) and similarly in Finland (1944–1970) to control alcohol consumption, by rationing of liquor.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Every citizen allowed to consume alcohol was given a booklet called a motbok (viinakortti in Finland), in which a stamp was added each time a purchase was made at Systembolaget (in Sweden) and Alko (in Finland).
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] A similar system also existed in Estonia between July 1, 1920, to December 31, 1925.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] The stamps were based on the amount of alcohol bought.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] When a certain amount of alcohol had been bought, the owner of the booklet had to wait until next month to buy more.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] The Medicinal Liquor Prescriptions Act of 1933 was a law passed by Congress in response to the abuse of medicinal liquor prescriptions during Prohibition.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Gilbert Paul Jordan (aka The Boozing Barber) was a Canadian serial killer who is believed to have committed the so-called "alcohol murders" between 1965–c.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] The consumption of alcohol is deeply embedded in social practices and rituals, often celebrated as a cornerstone of community gatherings and personal milestones.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Drinking culture is the set of traditions and social behaviours that surround the consumption of alcoholic beverages as a recreational drug and social lubricant.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Alcohol consumption is fully legal and available in most countries of the world.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Home made alcoholic beverages with low alcohol content like wine, and beer is also legal in most countries, but distilling moonshine outside of a registered distillery remains illegal in most of them.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Some majority-Muslim countries, such as Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Pakistan, Iran, and Libya prohibit the production, sale, and consumption of alcoholic beverages because they are forbidden by Islam.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Also, laws banning alcohol consumption are found in some Indian states as well as some Native American reservations in the U.S.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] In addition, there are regulations on alcohol sales and use in many countries throughout the world.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] For instance, the majority of countries have a minimum legal drinking age to purchase or consume alcoholic beverages, although there are often exceptions such as underage consumption of small amounts of alcohol with parental supervision.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Also, some countries have bans on public intoxication.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Drinking while driving or intoxicated driving is frequently outlawed, and it may be illegal to have an open container of alcohol or liquor bottle in an automobile, bus, or aircraft.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] The legality of sex under alcohol influence varies by country and the threshold of "too drunk" for sexual consent can be ambiguous.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Religion and alcohol have a complex history.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] The world's religions have had different relationships with alcohol, reflecting diverse cultural, social, and religious practices across different traditions.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] While some religions strictly prohibit alcohol consumption, viewing it as sinful or harmful to spiritual and physical well-being, others incorporate it into their rituals and ceremonies.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Throughout history, alcohol has held significant roles in religious observances, from the use of sacramental wine in Christian sacraments to the offering and moderate drinking of omiki (sacramental sake) in Shinto purification rituals.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] A study in 2015 found that alcohol and tobacco use combined resulted in a significant health burden, costing over a quarter of a billion disability-adjusted life years.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Illicit drug use caused tens of millions more disability-adjusted life years.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] According to *The Lancet*, 'four industries (tobacco, unhealthy food, fossil fuel, and alcohol) are responsible for at least a third of global deaths per year'.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] In 2024, the World Health Organization published a report including these figures.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Many Native Americans in the United States have been harmed by, or become addicted to, drinking alcohol.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] Qualitative analysis reveals that the alcohol industry likely misinforms the public about the dangers of alcohol, similar to the tobacco industry.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] The alcohol industry influences alcohol policy and health messages, including those for schoolchildren.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] The alcohol consumption recommendations (or *safe limits*) varies from no intake, to daily, weekly, or daily/weekly guidelines provided by health agencies of governments.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] A standard drink is a measure of alcohol consumption representing a fixed amount of pure ethanol, used in relation to recommendations about alcohol consumption and its relative risks to health.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-drug] The size of a standard drink varies from 8g to 20g across countries, but 10g alcohol (12.7 millilitres) is used in the World Health Organization (WHO) Alcohol Use Disorders Identification Test (AUDIT)'s questionnaire form example, and has been adopted by more countries than any other amount.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-in-malaysia] Based on a report released by International Organisation of Good Templars in 2016, Malaysia has the third highest tax on alcohol worldwide at 15%, behind Norway and Singapore which are predicted to keep increasing.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-in-malaysia] The country has an annual spending of RM2 billion on alcoholic drinks.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-in-malaysia] Prior to the Trans-Pacific Partnership, Malaysia together with Vietnam plans to drop import tariffs on beer, whisky, and other alcoholic drinks.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-in-malaysia] The tradition of brewing alcoholic drinks in Malaysia is most prominent in the island of Borneo.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-in-malaysia] Indigenous islanders traditionally drank home-made rice wine called tuak and tapai in their communal gatherings and harvest festivals of Gawai Dayak and Kaamatan.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-in-malaysia] Alcohol consumption in the Malay Peninsula has been less common since the introduction of Islam.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-in-malaysia] However, the production and consumption of alcohol (*arak*) has been a tradition since the time of Hang Tuah in the 15th century.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-in-malaysia] In the 20th century, palm toddy was popular among the local Indian and Chinese communities.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-in-malaysia] The British brought their own traditional brewed alcoholic drinks, such as beer and stout.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-in-malaysia] In the 1930, the first brewery was established in neighbouring British Singapore.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-in-malaysia] Since the British colonial times, Tiger Beer was the first commercial beer brewed in 1932 by Malayan Breweries Limited, a Singapore-based brewery which was formed from a merger between Heineken and Fraser and Neave (F&N).
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-in-malaysia] The beginning of alcohol production in Malaysia started in 1968, when two leading breweries, Guinness and Malayan, merged to form a new company known as Guinness Anchor Berhad.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-in-malaysia] In 1970, Carlsberg established its first brewery outside Kuala Lumpur in Shah Alam.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-in-malaysia] Both are since the only legal commercial breweries in Malaysia, which account for 95% of the total beer and stout volume in the country market.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-in-malaysia] In 2007, another two breweries known as Napex and Jaz brewed beer for pubs in the country, but both have since ceased from operation.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-in-malaysia] Beside local productions, many alcoholic drinks in the country are also imported from neighbouring countries such as Singapore, Thailand, Indonesia, Philippines and Vietnam.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-in-malaysia] The legal drinking age (purchasing) for Malaysia is 21 years old and above.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-in-malaysia] Since 2020, the legal limit for blood alcohol level while driving in Malaysia is 50 mg per 100 ml for blood test; 22 μg per 100 ml for breath test; and 67 mg per 100 ml for urine test.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-in-malaysia] Public drinking or public intoxication is not a crime in Malaysia, unless the drunken person caused "annoyance" towards others or exhibit "disorderly behaviour", which may be punished with a RM20 to RM25 fine or a 10 to 14 days jail under the Penal Code or Minor Offences Act 1955.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-in-malaysia] However, these laws are rarely enforced.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-in-malaysia] Any vendors, restaurants and retailers need a licence to serve or sell tap/draft beers, liquor and spirits in the country.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-in-malaysia] Bottled and canned beers are exempted from such licence requirements, which is why it is common to find many vendors and coffee houses serving alcohol in their premises without a licence.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-in-malaysia] Malaysia also imposes nationwide regulations for vendors to place their alcoholic drinks into separate refrigerators or storage places, although this was opposed by certain vendors in the state of Penang.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-in-malaysia] The high tax on alcohol has increased the price of alcoholic drinks in Malaysia, harming some drinkers who turn to unsafe alcohol smuggled in from neighbouring countries.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-in-malaysia] In 2018, around 45 people died in the country's worst methanol poisoning involving foreign workers and several Malaysians due to the consumption of cheap fake liquors acquired from the country's black markets.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-in-malaysia] Following Demerit Points System for Traffic Offences (KEJARA), a police officer or JPJ officer can take breath, blood or urine samples of drunk driver.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-in-malaysia] If alcohol content is found in the samples, a fine of RM 2000 or 6 months' imprisonment may be imposed for the first offence.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-in-malaysia] Alcohol is generally prohibited for Muslim consumers in the country as Malaysia's sharia law forbids Muslims from drinking alcohol.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-in-malaysia] Alcohol is mostly banned for Muslims in the states of Kelantan and Terengganu.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-related-traffic-crashes-in-the-united-states] This statistic includes all vehicular collisions (including bicycle and motorcycle) in which any alcohol has been consumed, or believed to have been consumed, by the driver, a passenger or a pedestrian associated with the incident.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-related-traffic-crashes-in-the-united-states] Thus, if a person who has consumed alcohol and has stopped for a red light is rear-ended by a completely sober but inattentive driver, the incident is listed as alcohol-related, although alcohol had nothing to do with causing the collision.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-related-traffic-crashes-in-the-united-states] Furthermore, if a sober motorist hits a drunk pedestrian, the incident is also listed as alcohol-related.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-related-traffic-crashes-in-the-united-states] Alcohol-related collisions are often mistakenly confused with alcohol-caused collisions.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-related-traffic-crashes-in-the-united-states] Some have criticized the NHTSA for compiling this statistic since it may give the impression that drunk drivers cause a much higher percentage of collisions and does not accurately reflect the problem of drunk driving in the United States.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-related-traffic-crashes-in-the-united-states] Nationally, 12.8% of all drivers involved in fatal collisions during 2013 are known to have been intoxicated according to the blood alcohol concentration (BAC laws) of their state.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-related-traffic-crashes-in-the-united-states] This number is based on a systematic examination of the official records of every incident involving a fatality during that year in the US.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-related-traffic-crashes-in-the-united-states] However, a majority of fatalities resulting from car crashes involving alcohol are from sober drivers who are hit by drunk drivers.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-related-traffic-crashes-in-the-united-states] The higher number (about 40%) commonly reported refers to collisions defined as alcohol-related as estimated by the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-related-traffic-crashes-in-the-united-states] Each year, The Century Council, a national non-profit organization funded by a group of alcohol manufacturers, compiles a document of alcohol-related traffic fatalities.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-related-traffic-crashes-in-the-united-states] Between 1991 and 2013, the rate of alcohol-related traffic fatalities (ARTF) per 100,000 population has decreased 52% nationally, and 79% among youth under 21.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-related-traffic-crashes-in-the-united-states] According to NHTSA, the 50 US states, the District of Columbia, and Puerto Rico all have BAC limits of 0.08 g/dL or lower.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-related-traffic-crashes-in-the-united-states] In 2016, in the USA, 10,497 people were killed in crashes involving alcohol-impaired drivers; this represents 28 percent of all traffic-related fatalities.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-related-traffic-crashes-in-the-united-states] Sixty-two percent of the people killed in such a crash were drivers, 29% occupants, and 9% non-occupants.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-related-traffic-crashes-in-the-united-states] In 2016, the states with the fewest fatalities due to alcohol-impaired drivers were Utah and Mississippi, with 128 and 52 killed (19%).
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-related-traffic-crashes-in-the-united-states] Among drivers with BAC levels of 0.08% or higher involved in fatal crashes, 75% are aged between 21 and 44.
[src:alcohol-in-malaysia/alcohol-related-traffic-crashes-in-the-united-states] Of all motorcyclists killed in crashes, 25% had BACs of 0.08% or greater.
